 produced by [[Wisconsin Public Radio]] and distributed through [[Public Radio International]]. Feldman is accompanied on-stage by Lyle Anderson, phone-answerer; and the Whad'ya Know Trio with John Thulin on piano, Jeff Hamann on bass, and, on road shows, [[Clyde Stubblefield]] on drums. Jeffry Eckels was the original full-time bass player from 1987 to 2003. Feldman was also accompanied by [[Jim Packard (radio host)|Jim Packard]] as announcer from the show's beginning until his death following the June 9, 2012, show from New York City. Sara Nics was the show's announcer from October 13, 2012 to March 28, 2015.<ref name=\"NicsDeparture\">{{cite press release\n | title = Sara Nics, 'Whad\u2019Ya Know?' Announcer, Departs For WNYC Project\n | publisher = Wisconsin Public Radio\n | date = \n | url = http://www.wpr.org/sara-nics-whad%E2%80%99ya-know-announcer-departs-wnyc-project\n | accessdate = 2015-04-25}}</ref> Stephanie Lee became the show's announcer in August 2015.<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite press release\n | title = Michael Feldman\u2019s Whad\u2019Ya Know?' Welcomes New Announcer Stephanie Lee\n | publisher = Wisconsin Public Radio\n | date = \n | url = http://www.wpr.org/michael-feldman%E2%80%99s-whad%E2%80%99ya-know-welcomes-new-announcer-stephanie-lee\n | accessdate = 2016-01-18}}</ref> The show was broadcast live with an audience from [[Monona Terrace]] in [[Madison, Wisconsin]]. Periodically, the show was taken on the road and broadcast from various other locations across the [[United States]]. The show was broadcast weekly, each Saturday at 10:00 AM [[time zone|CT]] ([[UTC-6]]) for two hours, and repeated throughout the week by syndication. Since the beginning of 2009, the entire show has also been available over the Internet as a [[podcast]]. The show aired its final WPR/PRI radio broadcast on June 25, 2016, with prior episodes archived on the show's website. Starting in the fall of 2016, Whad'ya Know became available online as a podcast.<ref>[http://www.wpr